title: Tate Modern

links.title: All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club

description: Modern art gallery in London, England
extract: Tate Modern is an art gallery in London, housing the United Kingdom's national collection of international modern and contemporary art, defined as from after 1900, and forms part of the Tate group together with Tate Britain, Tate Liverpool and Tate St Ives.

title: Blackfriars Bridge
description: Bridge over the River Thames in London
extract: Blackfriars Bridge is a road and foot traffic bridge over the River Thames in London, between Waterloo Bridge and Blackfriars Railway Bridge, carrying the A201 road.

title: London School of Economics
extract: The London School of Economics and Political Science (LSE) is a public research university in London, England, and a member institution of the University of London.

title: Millennium Bridge, London
description: Bridge over the River Thames in England
extract: The Millennium Bridge, officially known as the London Millennium Footbridge, is a steel suspension bridge for pedestrians crossing the River Thames in London, England, linking Bankside with the City of London.

title: Newgate Prison
extract: Newgate Prison was a prison at the corner of Newgate Street and Old Bailey Street just inside the City of London, England, originally at the site of Newgate, a gate in the Roman London Wall.

title: London Waterloo station
description: Central London terminus on the National Rail network in the United Kingdom
extract: Waterloo station (), also known as London Waterloo, is a central London terminus on the National Rail network in the United Kingdom, in the Waterloo area of the London Borough of Lambeth.

title: International Institute for Strategic Studies
extract: The International Institute for Strategic Studies (IISS) is a British research institute or think tank in the area of international affairs.

title: Waterloo tube station
extract: Waterloo is a London Underground station located beneath Waterloo National Rail station.

title: St Paul's Cathedral
description: Cathedral in the City of London, England
extract: St Paul's Cathedral is an Anglican cathedral in London, England, and is the seat of the Bishop of London.

title: Savoy Palace
description: Noble townhouse in London, destroyed during the Peasant's Revolt of 1381
extract: The Savoy Palace, considered the grandest nobleman's townhouse of medieval London, was the residence of prince John of Gaunt until it was destroyed during rioting in the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.

title: River Fleet
extract: The River Fleet is the largest of London's subterranean rivers, all of which today contain foul water for treatment.

title: John Leland (antiquary)
extract: John Leland or Leyland (13 September, c. 1503 – 18 April 1552) was an English poet and antiquary.Leland has been described as "the father of English local history and bibliography".

title: Eurovision Song Contest 1960
extract: The Eurovision Song Contest 1960 was the fifth edition of the annual Eurovision Song Contest, held on Tuesday 29 March 1960 at the Royal Festival Hall in London, United Kingdom, and hosted by British television presenter and actress Catherine Boyle.

title: King's College London
extract: King's College London (informally King's or KCL) is a public research university located in London, England.

title: Royal National Theatre
extract: The Royal National Theatre of Great Britain, commonly known as the National Theatre (NT) within the UK and as the National Theatre of Great Britain internationally, is a performing arts venue and associated theatre company located in London, England.

title: Sainsbury's
extract: J Sainsbury plc, trading as Sainsbury's, is a British supermarket and the second largest chain of supermarkets in the United Kingdom, with a 14.6% share of UK supermarket sales in September 2022.Founded in 1869 by John James Sainsbury with a shop in Drury Lane, London, the company was the largest UK retailer of groceries for most of the 20th century.

title: London Stock Exchange

title: Globe Theatre
